**Bug description**
When I specify the default Advisor myself, if I don't explicitly specify the default Advisor for the framework again, I will report an error when calling ChatClient.

```
@Configuration
public class AiModelConfig {

    @Bean
    public ChatClient teacherModelClient(ChatModel deepSeekChatModel) {
        return ChatClient.builder(deepSeekChatModel)
                .defaultSystem("""
                        You are a friendly chat bot that answers question in the voice of a {voice}
                        """)
                .defaultAdvisors(
                        // i just want to set one advisor about SimpleLoggerAdvisor , but i found if i dont set 
                        // ChatModelCallAdvisor , when i call teacherModelClient , it will return me a error .
                        //ChatModelCallAdvisor.builder().chatModel(deepSeekChatModel).build(),
                        SimpleLoggerAdvisor.builder().build()
                )
                .build();
    }

}
```

error log : 

```
java.lang.IllegalStateException: No CallAdvisors available to execute
	at org.springframework.ai.chat.client.advisor.DefaultAroundAdvisorChain.nextCall(DefaultAroundAdvisorChain.java:97) ~[spring-ai-client-chat-1.0.0.jar:1.0.0]
	at org.springframework.ai.chat.client.DefaultChatClient$DefaultCallResponseSpec.lambda$doGetObservableChatClientResponse$1(DefaultChatClient.java:469) ~[spring-ai-client-chat-1.0.0.jar:1.0.0]
	at io.micrometer.observation.Observation.observe(Observation.java:564) ~[micrometer-observation-1.15.1.jar:1.15.1]
	at org.springframework.ai.chat.client.DefaultChatClient$DefaultCallResponseSpec.doGetObservableChatClientResponse(DefaultChatClient.java:467) ~[spring-ai-client-chat-1.0.0.jar:1.0.0]
	at org.springframework.ai.chat.client.DefaultChatClient$DefaultCallResponseSpec.doGetObservableChatClientResponse(DefaultChatClient.java:446) ~[spring-ai-client-chat-1.0.0.jar:1.0.0]
	at org.springframework.ai.chat.client.DefaultChatClient$DefaultCallResponseSpec.content(DefaultChatClient.java:441) ~[spring-ai-client-chat-1.0.0.jar:1.0.0]
	at us.zoom.mq.springai001.controller.AIController.completion(AIController.java:27) ~[classes/:na]
	at java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke0(Native Method) ~[na:na]
```


Also i check in Spring AI doc :
**The Advisor Chain, created by the Spring AI framework, allows sequential invocation of multiple advisors ordered by their getOrder() values. The lower values are executed first. The last advisor, added automatically, sends the request to the LLM.**

I don't think the actual result is consistent with what the document says, and it will be added automatically. Should we judge whether the user has specified the default Advisor of the framework when initializing ChatClient? If not, we need to automatically add the default Advisor to the Advisor Chain of ChatClient.

**Environment**
Spring AI Version : 1.0.0
Java Version : openjdk-17
SpringBoot Version:3.5.3

**Steps to reproduce**
use this chatClient config : 
```
@Configuration
public class AiModelConfig {

    @Bean
    public ChatClient teacherModelClient(ChatModel deepSeekChatModel) {
        return ChatClient.builder(deepSeekChatModel)
                .defaultSystem("""
                        You are a friendly chat bot that answers question in the voice of a {voice}
                        """)
                .defaultAdvisors(
                        SimpleLoggerAdvisor.builder().build()
                )
                .build();
    }

}
```

**Expected behavior**
When I don't set the default Advisor for the framework, I can automatically set it for me.

**Minimal Complete Reproducible example**
```
@Configuration
public class AiModelConfig {

    @Bean
    public ChatClient teacherModelClient(ChatModel deepSeekChatModel) {
        return ChatClient.builder(deepSeekChatModel)
                .defaultSystem("""
                        You are a friendly chat bot that answers question in the voice of a {voice}
                        """)
                .defaultAdvisors(
                        SimpleLoggerAdvisor.builder().build()
                )
                .build();
    }

}
```

comments.body:
Test Code：
```
@RestController
class AIController {

    @Autowired
    private ChatClient teacherModelClient;

    @GetMapping("/ai")
    Map<String, String> completion(@RequestParam(value = "message", defaultValue = "Tell me a joke") String message, String voice) {
        ChatClient.CallResponseSpec response = this.teacherModelClient.
                prompt()
                .system(sp -> sp.param("voice", voice))
                .user(message)
                .call();
        ChatResponse chatResponse = response.chatResponse();
        System.out.println(chatResponse);
        String voice1 = response
                .content();
        return Map.of("completion", voice1
        );
    }
}
```

Calling the `call()` method doesn't actually trigger the large model. It only tells SpringAI whether to use a synchronous or streaming call. 
The actual model call happens when you invoke `content()` or `chatResponse()`. 

You can get the content from `ChatResponse` like this:
```java
ChatResponse chatResponse = response.chatResponse();
        System.out.println(chatResponse);
        String voice1 = Optional.ofNullable(chatResponse)
                .map(ChatResponse::getResult)
                .map(Generation::getOutput)
                .map(AbstractMessage::getText)
                .orElse(null);
        System.out.println(voice1);
```
